1 Abstract

This article takes a critical computational approach to the question of school desegregation in response to the 1954 Brown v. Board United States Supreme Court decision . I conduct a conceptual replication of the 1974 work of Michael Giles entitled Measuring School Desegregation published in the Journal of Negro Education. I then use mathematical modeling techniques to engage contemporary data in relation to Giles framing around the issue of quantifying school desegregation. Findings reveal that three of the four attributed models did not account for the systems to which school desegregation was to be a historical marker. We find U.S. data on racial segregation maintains that between-class and within-class segregation measures persit, with the primary marker of change being on between-class differnces (Black vs.White). This difference is attributed to the ongoing racialization of students in U.S. schools under the guise of white racial superiority. Still, however, we find through a citation analysiis of ongoing research on the Brown decision, critical scholars continue to not only critique but provide possible responses to inform critical shifts in U.S. education systems.

Keywords

Brown v. Board of Education, desegregation, segregation, race, mathematical modeling

Citation

Alexander, N. N. (2024). Quantifying School Desegregation.

5 Mathematical models

The index of dissimilarity is a widely used measure of segregation that examines the demographic makeup of a given geographic area, \(G\), based on the distribution of two groups across a set of \(N\) neighborhoods which constitute area \(G\). Despite its limitations when considering non-binary measures of racial segregation, the index of dissimilarity provides the unique ability to explore more focused conceptions of racism|known as anti-Blackness|that play out at the neighborhood level.

Modern data science applications and tools have produced new lines of scholarly inquiry that are increasingly critical. This critical stance is often a combination or result of advances in mathematical modeling capabilities and shifts in the research priorities at sub-disciplinary levels. Importantly, these inquiries are also a result of a decades long focus among educators, and especially those educations in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM), looking to integrate group-worthy, culturally-relevant, and justice-oriented practices.

Moreover, increases in the collection and availability of data at more local levels, which have presented opportunities for more acute analyses. These burgeoning fields of study, such as mathematical sociology and mathematical psychology, can take into consideration both the formal and more intuitive formations of the social world. In mathematical psychology, for example, these interdisciplinary connections have expanded back into the more dominant fields as new tools are acquired that allow researchers to ask and answer previously unanswerable questions. One example at the intersection of data science and interdisciplinary study is the rapid expansion of research on neural networks.

As these new findings and tools emerge, researchers have been able to connect data sources to more nuanced and critical frameworks. This integration|of more localized data and new conceptual and theoretical frameworks|has increased the possibility of interdisciplinary analyses that consider the logical and computational matters alongside real-world applications and examples in real-time. The field of mathematical sociology is another example of a rapidly increasing interdisciplinary domain of study, and in the context of data science may be best known for its contributions to inquiries related to social networks.

5.1 Model 1: Index of Dissimilarity

The index of dissimilarity, \(D\), is a measure that scores the evenness of two groups across a set of indexed neighborhoods, \(n_i\), within some larger component geographic area, \(G\). \(D\) can also be interpreted as the calculated proportion of one of two groups that would need to move to different neighborhoods in order to produce a distribution that matches that of the larger geographic area. In both of these instances, \(D\) can be used to measure segregation as a function of neighborhood composition where a score of \(0\) indicates a fully integrated geographical area and a score of \(1\) represents complete segregation. The basic formula for the index of dissimilarity is:

\[\begin{equation}\label{eq:1} D = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \Bigl|\frac{a_i}{A} - \frac{b_i}{B}\Bigr| \end{equation}\]

with \(a_i\), \(b_i\) \(\in\) \(\mathbb{Z}^{0+}\) where \(a_i\) is the population of group A in the \(i^{th}\) neighborhood; A is the total population of group A in the broader geographical area \(G\); \(b_i\) is the population of group B in the \(i^{th}\) neighborhood; and B is the total population of group B in the broader geographical area \(G\). The model assumes the existence of at least two groups in \(G\) such that \(A \neq 0\) and \(B \neq 0\).

The basic formula for \(D\) has been applied to a variety of contexts and situations and given its wide range can be said to apply to any set of discrete categorical variables beyond demographic measures. As a result, we expand on this base model to explore connections to the theoretical frameworks discussed in Section 2.

5.1.0.1 Linear algebra perspective

Importantly, there are key connections to linear algebra for the index of dissimilarity that prove useful for computation, data wrangling, and data analysis. When viewed from a linear algebra perspective, we provide direct connections to the structure of data sets that house information on a set of indexed neighborhoods. These data can be used to examine dynamic models of the same geographical area \(G\).

First, we assume that the set \(G\) indexes a set of non-overlapping, or partitioned, neighborhoods to be analyzed such that

\[\begin{equation}\label{eq:2} G = \{n_i | i \in \mathbb{N}\} \end{equation}\]

or, more intuitively, \(G\) = {neighborhood 1, neighborhood 2, , neighborhood N}. The partition of the set \(G\) is the set of non-empty subsets of neighborhoods in G such that every neighborhood, \(n_i\), in G is in exactly one of these subsets. Namely, we say that G is a disjoint union of the subsets. The elements of the subsets are members of the two groups, \(A\) and \(B\).

We then create two vectors and which show the number of each of the two groups of individuals in \(A\) and \(B\), respectively, in each neighborhood of G producing the following:

\[\begin{equation}\label{eq:3} \textbf{a} = [ a_1, a_2, ..., a_N] \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation}\label{eq:4} \textbf{b} = [ b_1, b_2, ..., b_N] \end{equation}\]
